TEXT(beginproblem()); # standard preamble to each problem.


$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

Context("Numeric");

$r = random(11,29,2);
$dec = $r/100;
$b = 1+$dec;
$d = round(log(2)/log($b)*10)/10;

BEGIN_TEXT

Find the doubling time for a city whose population is growing by $r$PERCENT per year.
$BR
$BR
The doubling time is \{ ans_rule(10) \} years. (Round to the nearest 0.1 years.) 
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}

END_TEXT

ANS( Real("$d")->cmp(tolerance=>0.1,tolType=>"absolute") );

# ANS( num_cmp($d) );

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 

Since the growth factor is $b =1 + $dec, the formula for the city's population, with an initial population of $BITALIC a $EITALIC and time $BITALIC t $EITALIC in years, is \( P = a($b)^t\).
$BR $SPACE $BR
The population doubles for the first time when $BITALIC P $EITALIC = 2${BITALIC}a${EITALIC}.  Thus, we solve for $BITALIC t $EITALIC after setting $BITALIC P $EITALIC equal to $BITALIC 2a $EITALIC to give us the doubling time:
$BR $SPACE $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ 2a = a($b)^t \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ 2 = ($b)^t \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \log{2} = \log{\left( ($b)^t \right)} \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \log{2} = t \ \log{($b)} \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ t = \frac{\log{2}}{\log{($b)}} \approx $d \).
$BR $SPACE $BR
So the doubling time is about $d years.
$BR
END_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();   # This should be the last executable line in the problem.